Based on the test name `shouldMatchCaptureArgumentsWhenArgsCountDoesNOTMatch` and the code, it looks like the issue is in the `captureArgumentsFrom` method where it doesn't properly handle cases when the number of matchers doesn't match the number of arguments. 

Looking at the test:

```java
@Test
public void shouldMatchCaptureArgumentsWhenArgsCountDoesNOTMatch() throws Exception {
    //given
    mock.varargs();  // This creates an invocation with 0 arguments
    Invocation invocation = getLastInvocation();

    //when
    InvocationMatcher invocationMatcher = new InvocationMatcher(invocation, (List) asList(new LocalizedMatcher(AnyVararg.ANY_VARARG)));

    //then
    invocationMatcher.captureArgumentsFrom(invocation);  // This should not throw exception even though args count doesn't match
}
```

The problem is in the `captureArgumentsFrom` method. It assumes all matchers have corresponding arguments, but when there are more matchers than arguments, it tries to access `i.getArguments()[k]` where `k` exceeds the bounds of the arguments array.

Let me examine the fix needed:

